                    "Found in vehicle, GCS 11, BGL 2.1 on arrival. MedicAlert bracelet confirmed Type 1 diabetes. Mechanism indicated C-spine precautions. He couldn't swallow safely so we gave IM Glucagon 1 mg with EOC authorisation at [time]. He vomited during transport — airway was managed with suction, no aspiration."</p>

                    <p><strong>A — Assessment:</strong><br>
                    "Current status: GCS 15, BGL 4.2. He's had some biscuits. Airway clear post-suction. C-collar and vacuum mattress in place — cervical spine not cleared. No obvious traumatic injuries but mechanism was significant."</p>

                    <p><strong>R — Request/Recommendation:</strong><br>
                    "He'll need review for why he went hypo — was it missed meal, insulin dose issue, something else? And imaging to clear his C-spine. Happy to answer any questions."</p>
                </div>

                <div class="teaching-points">
                    <h5>Key Teaching Points</h5>
                    <ul>
                        <li>ISBAR provides structure — the ED knows what's coming</li>
                        <li>Lead with the headline: "MVA caused by hypoglycaemia"</li>
                        <li>Include the Glucagon dose and time — this is important for ongoing management</li>
                        <li>Mention the vomiting/suction event — it's relevant to aspiration risk</li>
                        <li>Be clear about what's NOT cleared: C-spine needs imaging</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 14: Debrief -->
        <section class="section">
            <div class="section-header">
                <div class="section-icon">💭</div>
                <h2>Debrief (10–15 minutes)</h2>
            </div>

            <h3>Reflective Questions</h3>
            
            <div class="debrief-question">
                <strong>1. Protocol Application:</strong> Walk me through the CPP-009-AO decision tree for this patient. Why couldn't we give oral glucose? What triggered the Glucagon?
            </div>

            <div class="debrief-question">
                <strong>2. Clinical Reasoning:</strong> The protocol says "measure BGL on all patients with altered conscious state, including trauma." Why is this so important? What would have happened if we'd assumed this was just a head injury?
            </div>

            <div class="debrief-question">
                <strong>3. Assessment Skills:</strong> How did you assess whether Barry could swallow safely? What's the "cough test" and why does it work?
            </div>

            <div class="debrief-question">
                <strong>4. Prioritisation:</strong> How did you balance treating the hypoglycaemia against maintaining C-spine precautions? Both were important — how did you manage both?
            </div>

            <div class="debrief-question">
                <strong>5. Airway Emergency:</strong> When Barry vomited, were you surprised? What does the protocol warn us about Glucagon that should have prepared you?
            </div>

            <div class="debrief-question">
                <strong>6. Team Coordination:</strong> How did you divide tasks between clinician and driver roles? What worked well?
            </div>

            <div class="debrief-question">
                <strong>7. Real-World Application:</strong> What's the one thing from tonight's session you'll remember on your next job with an altered patient?
            </div>

            <div class="take-home">
                <h4>Take-Home Messages</h4>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>"Measure BGL on all patients with altered conscious state, including trauma"</strong> — it's in the protocol for a reason</li>
                    <li><strong>Cough test</strong> — quick, simple indicator of safe swallowing (adequate GCS)</li>
                    <li><strong>Least invasive first</strong> — oral glucose if they can swallow, Glucagon if they can't</li>
                    <li><strong>EOC Clinician consultation</strong> — required before giving Glucagon</li>
                    <li><strong>Glucagon causes nausea</strong> — anticipate vomiting during recovery</li>
                    <li><strong>Complex carbs after recovery</strong> — sustains the BGL rise</li>
                    <li><strong>Suction saves lives</strong> — know where it is and practice using it</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Section 15: Scenario Variations -->
        <section class="section">
            <div class="section-header">
                <div class="section-icon">🔄</div>
                <h2>Optional Scenario Variations</h2>
            </div>

            <div class="toggle-section">
                <button class="toggle-btn" onclick="toggleContent(this)">
                    Variation 1: Patient Responds to Oral Glucose
                </button>
                <div class="toggle-content">
                    <p><strong>Change:</strong> Patient is GCS 13, follows commands, coughs on request</p>
                    <ul class="checklist">
                        <li>Cough test positive = safe to give oral glucose</li>
                        <li>Administer oral glucose up to 15 g (glucose gel)</li>
                        <li>Recheck BGL every 5 minutes</li>
                        <li>Once BGL &gt; 3.5, offer complex carbohydrates</li>
                        <li>No need for Glucagon or EOC consultation</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p><strong>Teaching focus:</strong> The simpler pathway — "least invasive therapy"</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="toggle-section">
                <button class="toggle-btn" onclick="toggleContent(this)">
                    Variation 2: Glucagon Ineffective
                </button>
                <div class="toggle-content">
                    <p><strong>Change:</strong> 15 minutes post-Glucagon, BGL only rises to 2.5 mmol/L, GCS unchanged</p>
                    <ul class="checklist">
                        <li>Glucagon requires liver glycogen — may be depleted</li>
                        <li>Contact EOC Clinician — report ineffective response</li>
                        <li>EOC may request ICP/Paramedic backup if available</li>
                        <li>Priority transport — patient needs IV glucose (hospital only)</li>
                        <li>Continue monitoring, maintain airway</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p><strong>Teaching focus:</strong> Glucagon limitations and escalation when treatment fails</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="toggle-section">
                <button class="toggle-btn" onclick="toggleContent(this)">
                    Variation 3: Paediatric Patient (8 years old)
                </button>
                <div class="toggle-content">
                    <p><strong>Change:</strong> Passenger is an 8-year-old child, Type 1 diabetic, same presentation</p>
                    <ul class="checklist">
                        <li>Protocol applies: patient ≥ 2 years with BGL &lt; 3.5</li>
                        <li>If oral glucose cannot be given → consult EOC Clinician</li>
                        <li>Glucagon dose: <strong>1 mg IM</strong> (patient ≥ 6 years or ≥ 25 kg)</li>
                        <li>If child was 4 years old: dose would be <strong>0.5 mg IM</strong></li>
                        <li>Same management principles apply</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p><strong>Teaching focus:</strong> Paediatric dosing from CPP-009-AO</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="toggle-section">
                <button class="toggle-btn" onclick="toggleContent(this)">
                    Variation 4: Patient Seizes
                </button>
                <div class="toggle-content">
                    <p><strong>Change:</strong> Before Glucagon can be given, Barry has a generalised tonic-clonic seizure</p>
                    <ul class="checklist">
                        <li>Hypoglycaemia can cause seizures — protocol mentions this</li>
                        <li>Protect from injury — can't remove from vehicle mid-seizure</li>
                        <li>Time the seizure — note duration</li>
                        <li>Do NOT restrain — let it run</li>
                        <li>Prepare suction for post-ictal phase</li>
                        <li>Post-seizure: Give IM Glucagon (EOC authorised) — treats the cause</li>
                        <li>Contact EOC if seizure &gt; 5 minutes</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p><strong>Teaching focus:</strong> Hypoglycaemic seizures — treat the underlying cause</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Protocol Quick Reference -->
        <section class="section">
            <div class="section-header">
                <div class="section-icon">📋</div>
                <h2>Quick Reference: CPP-009-AO</h2>
            </div>

            <div class="protocol-box">
                <h4>Hypoglycaemia - AO (CPP-009-AO) Summary</h4>
                
                <table class="obs-table">
                    <tr>
                        <th>Patient Group</th>
                        <th>BGL Threshold</th>
                        <th>Management</th>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Adults & children ≥ 2 yrs</td>
                        <td>&lt; 3.5 mmol/L</td>
                        <td>Oral glucose 15g if can swallow (cough test)</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>If oral glucose cannot be given</td>
                        <td>—</td>
                        <td>Consult EOC Clinician</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>≥ 6 yrs (or ≥ 25 kg)</td>
                        <td>—</td>
                        <td>IM Glucagon <strong>1 mg</strong> (EOC authorised)</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>≥ 2 yrs to &lt; 6 yrs (or &lt; 25 kg)</td>
                        <td>—</td>
                        <td>IM Glucagon <strong>0.5 mg</strong> (EOC authorised)</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>&lt; 2 yrs</td>
                        <td>&lt; 3.5 mmol/L</td>
                        <td>Consult EOC first — oral glucose gel or IM Glucagon 0.5 mg</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Neonates</td>
                        <td>&lt; 2.5 mmol/L</td>
                        <td>Consult EOC Clinician</td>
                    </tr>
                </table>

                <div class="info-box" style="margin-top: 16px;">
                    <strong>Key Principles:</strong>
                    <ul style="margin-left: 20px; margin-top: 8px;">
                        <li>Least invasive therapy that increases blood glucose</li>
                        <li>Measure BGL in ALL altered conscious states, including trauma</li>
                        <li>Cough = good indicator of safe swallowing</li>
                        <li>If recovery occurs → offer complex carbohydrates</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

    </main>

    <script>
        // Progress bar
        window.addEventListener('scroll', () => {
            const winScroll = document.body.scrollTop || document.documentElement.scrollTop;
            const height = document.documentElement.scrollHeight - document.documentElement.clientHeight;
            const scrolled = (winScroll / height) * 100;
            document.getElementById('progressFill').style.width = scrolled + '%';
        });

        // Fade in on scroll
        const sections = document.querySelectorAll('.section');
        
        const observerOptions = {
            threshold: 0.1,
            rootMargin: '0px 0px -50px 0px'
        };

        const observer = new IntersectionObserver((entries) => {
            entries.forEach(entry => {
                if (entry.isIntersecting) {
                    entry.target.classList.add('visible');
                }
            });
        }, observerOptions);

        sections.forEach(section => {
            observer.observe(section);
        });

        // Make first section visible immediately
        document.querySelector('.section').classList.add('visible');

        // Toggle sections
        function toggleContent(button) {
            button.classList.toggle('active');
            const content = button.nextElementSibling;
            content.classList.toggle('show');
        }
    </script>

